1
00:05:26,145 --> 00:05:29,346
I'm sorry! I'm sorry! I'm sorry!

2
00:05:30,146 --> 00:05:32,813
It's all right. I'm not gonna hurt you.

3
00:05:33,105 --> 00:05:34,266
What do you want?

4
00:05:34,355 --> 00:05:35,219
I thought you were...

5
00:05:35,313 --> 00:05:36,392
What?

6
00:05:37,314 --> 00:05:38,688
I don't know.

7
00:05:50,399 --> 00:05:53,102
Help! Help!

8
00:05:56,484 --> 00:05:58,640
Help! Help!

9
00:06:02,360 --> 00:06:03,438
Stop!

10
00:06:09,653 --> 00:06:13,729
- What? What?
- It's okay. Come here.

11
00:06:33,948 --> 00:06:36,947
It's okay. Calm down.
Everything's gonna be fine.

12
00:06:37,116 --> 00:06:38,277
What was in there?

13
00:06:38,491 --> 00:06:40,398
Just gimme a minute
to figure things out.

14
00:06:40,491 --> 00:06:43,490
- Why were you afraid of that room?
- Gimme a minute I said.

15
00:06:49,159 --> 00:06:51,281
How many people are in this thing?

16
00:06:53,743 --> 00:06:56,695
Listen. We can't go
climbing around in here.

17
00:06:56,952 --> 00:06:58,066
Why not?

18
00:06:59,995 --> 00:07:02,530
- There are traps.
- What do you mean traps?

19
00:07:02,662 --> 00:07:05,826
Booby traps. I looked
into a room down there and

20
00:07:05,912 --> 00:07:07,654
something almost cut my head off.

21
00:07:12,038 --> 00:07:16,531
Holy cats. Holy, holy cats.

22
00:07:35,792 --> 00:07:38,625
You alright? Mister?

23
00:07:41,377 --> 00:07:42,158
Worth!

24
00:07:47,503 --> 00:07:48,284
Don't worry.

25
00:07:54,629 --> 00:07:55,542
I hit my head.

26
00:07:55,879 --> 00:08:00,454
Let me take a look at that.
I'm a doctor. It doesn't look that bad.

27
00:08:04,506 --> 00:08:06,047
What the hell are you doing?

28
00:08:19,425 --> 00:08:22,044
Hey, old man,
did you hear what I said?

29
00:08:42,887 --> 00:08:47,012
Motion detectors. Integrated
into the walls. Tough to spot.

30
00:08:48,722 --> 00:08:51,803
Oh god, oh god, oh god.

31
00:08:55,264 --> 00:08:58,595
Wait a second.
Let's all just relax for a minute.

32
00:09:00,807 --> 00:09:02,798
Does anybody remember
how they got here?

33
00:09:10,976 --> 00:09:12,006
Perogies.

34
00:09:15,893 --> 00:09:17,090
I was eating dinner.

35
00:09:17,643 --> 00:09:18,923
Perogies. Cheese and potatoes.

36
00:09:19,019 --> 00:09:21,686
I ran out of sour cream and then
I went to the fridge and then...

37
00:09:22,769 --> 00:09:23,634
I don't know.

38
00:09:24,811 --> 00:09:27,514
You? Leaven?

39
00:09:29,229 --> 00:09:32,677
I, I just went to bed and...

40
00:09:35,521 --> 00:09:36,552
What about you?

41
00:09:38,730 --> 00:09:40,307
I just woke up here.

42
00:09:40,606 --> 00:09:41,767
Middle of the night.

43
00:09:42,564 --> 00:09:45,100
It's like Chile. They always come
in the middle of the night.

44
00:09:46,190 --> 00:09:47,055
Who?

45
00:09:47,148 --> 00:09:49,720
Only the goverment could build
something this ugly.

46
00:09:49,816 --> 00:09:50,929
It ain't government.

47
00:09:51,024 --> 00:09:53,394
- Then what is it?
- I don't know.

48
00:09:54,775 --> 00:09:56,019
Aliens.

49
00:10:00,609 --> 00:10:02,814
Please.
We're spooked enough as it is.

50
00:10:02,901 --> 00:10:07,606
Let's rule out aliens for now and
concentrate on what we know.

51
00:10:07,694 --> 00:10:08,891
My mom's gonna freak.

52
00:10:09,652 --> 00:10:10,434
Rennes?

53
00:10:11,361 --> 00:10:15,058
- I just won't be there. They'll freak.
- What do you think, Rennes?

54
00:10:15,862 --> 00:10:18,232
We won't solve jack shit sittin' still.

55
00:10:18,571 --> 00:10:20,810
I'm moving in a straight line
'till I get to the end.

56
00:10:21,404 --> 00:10:22,945
All right, I tend to agree.

57
00:10:23,321 --> 00:10:25,692
- Shouldn't we wait here?
- For what?

58
00:10:26,113 --> 00:10:27,606
To see if anybody comes.

59
00:10:27,905 --> 00:10:29,149
No one is gonna come.

60
00:10:29,322 --> 00:10:33,187
Look. There is a way in here,
so there's gotta be a way out.

61
00:10:33,740 --> 00:10:35,814
We can avoid
the traps using the boot.

62
00:10:36,365 --> 00:10:39,814
Holloway is it?
What do you think? Look for an exit?

63
00:10:40,574 --> 00:10:41,404
Okay.

64
00:10:42,450 --> 00:10:43,563
What about you?

65
00:10:43,825 --> 00:10:47,156
- It can't be that simple.
- It won't be that simple.

66
00:10:47,867 --> 00:10:51,280
Look around.
Take a good long looksee.

67
00:10:53,118 --> 00:10:55,405
'Cause I got a feeling
it's looking at us.

68
00:11:03,578 --> 00:11:05,202
I just want to wake up.

69
00:11:12,205 --> 00:11:14,990
Leaven. We can do this.

70
00:11:15,664 --> 00:11:18,781
We just have to stay calm
and work together as a team.

71
00:11:20,540 --> 00:11:23,324
There's gonna be a lot of people
looking for us on the outside.

72
00:11:23,915 --> 00:11:24,863
I'm a cop.

73
00:11:25,665 --> 00:11:26,614
All right?

74
00:11:28,124 --> 00:11:29,701
- You're a cop?
- Yeah.

75
00:11:30,833 --> 00:11:32,990
I'm gonna get you out of here.
I promise.

76
00:11:33,875 --> 00:11:35,617
You gotta be with me on this one.

77
00:11:40,876 --> 00:11:41,658
Okay.

78
00:11:53,545 --> 00:11:54,576
Boot it!

79
00:12:02,589 --> 00:12:03,453
Clean.

80
00:12:23,384 --> 00:12:24,877
That one sounded closer.

81
00:12:25,467 --> 00:12:28,087
It's mechanical. It seems
to come at regular intervals.

82
00:12:28,468 --> 00:12:30,340
Maybe it's the ventilation system.

83
00:12:30,552 --> 00:12:33,219
- No vents.
- No kidding, I'm boiling.

84
00:12:36,844 --> 00:12:37,757
What is it?

85
00:12:41,220 --> 00:12:42,334
Serial numbers?

86
00:12:42,679 --> 00:12:45,428
Room numbers.
They're different in each room.

87
00:12:45,929 --> 00:12:50,006
Oh great. There are only 566 millions
400 thousand rooms in this thing.

88
00:12:50,097 --> 00:12:51,424
Well, there better not be?

89
00:12:51,514 --> 00:12:53,635
We have about 3 days
without food and water

90
00:12:53,722 --> 00:12:55,713
before we are too weak to move.

91
00:12:56,056 --> 00:12:57,763
Well, they have to feed us,
don't they?

92
00:12:59,182 --> 00:13:00,260
Holloway.

93
00:13:00,348 --> 00:13:05,469
Oh, we have heat, stress, physical
exsection, i.e., dehydratation,

94
00:13:05,558 --> 00:13:08,924
headaches, dizziness, disorientation,
confused mental processes.

95
00:13:09,017 --> 00:13:11,932
The body eventually begins
to break down its own tissue.

96
00:13:13,726 --> 00:13:15,053
Suck on it.

97
00:13:18,893 --> 00:13:20,766
Keeps the saliva flowing.

98
00:13:39,189 --> 00:13:41,475
- What?
- The air seems dry in there.

99
00:13:41,772 --> 00:13:42,720
Trapped?

100
00:13:43,023 --> 00:13:44,930
Molecular chemical sensor.

101
00:13:45,065 --> 00:13:47,102
Why the hell didn't
the boot set it off?

102
00:13:47,273 --> 00:13:48,517
The boot's not alive.

103
00:13:49,107 --> 00:13:52,058
Detects hydrogen sulphide
excreted from the skin.

104
00:13:52,482 --> 00:13:54,722
How is it you know
so much about sensors, Renz?

105
00:13:59,942 --> 00:14:04,435
Renn. Not Renz. It's French.

106
00:14:04,610 --> 00:14:06,684
Fine, you're French.
I'm asking how you...

107
00:14:09,735 --> 00:14:12,734
Renn. Sensor expert,

108
00:14:12,819 --> 00:14:14,016
about the right age.

109
00:14:14,861 --> 00:14:16,141
I don't believe it.

110
00:14:19,821 --> 00:14:22,392
- This guy is the Wren.
- The what?

111
00:14:22,696 --> 00:14:26,773
He's the Wren. The Bird of Attica.
Flew the coop on 6 major prisons.

112
00:14:27,280 --> 00:14:28,311
Seven.

113
00:14:28,447 --> 00:14:30,237
You're kidding, right?

114
00:14:31,156 --> 00:14:32,400
You can get us out.

115
00:14:32,614 --> 00:14:33,609
Maybe.

116
00:14:34,198 --> 00:14:35,821
An escape artist.

117
00:14:35,907 --> 00:14:37,814
Yeah, I'm Harry fucking Houdini.

118
00:14:40,116 --> 00:14:42,652
The only reason I dragged you
this far is 'cause I need your boots.

119
00:14:43,408 --> 00:14:45,897
If you don't smarten up,
I'll be gone like that.

120
00:14:47,284 --> 00:14:48,563
No more talking.

121
00:14:49,784 --> 00:14:51,063
No more guessing.

122
00:14:52,034 --> 00:14:55,317
Don't even think about nothing
that's not right in front of you.

123
00:14:56,035 --> 00:14:57,907
That's the real challenge.

124
00:14:59,286 --> 00:15:01,857
You got to save yourselves
from yourselves.

125
00:15:11,830 --> 00:15:12,742
Merde.

126
00:15:22,706 --> 00:15:24,034
Get him out!

127
00:15:58,713 --> 00:15:59,957
Oh my god!

128
00:16:08,173 --> 00:16:12,996
So, it was electro chemical or
whatever, right? And he missed it.

129
00:16:13,799 --> 00:16:17,330
The Wren. That's great!
That's fuckin' great!

130
00:16:29,885 --> 00:16:33,500
All right. It's time
to reassess this place.

131
00:16:33,760 --> 00:16:36,084
I've been over it again and again.

132
00:16:36,219 --> 00:16:38,293
Why would they throw
innocent people in here?

133
00:16:38,386 --> 00:16:39,844
Are we being punished?

134
00:16:40,762 --> 00:16:43,251
I've never done anything
to deserve this.

135
00:16:43,720 --> 00:16:44,917
Forget about all that!

136
00:16:46,221 --> 00:16:48,970
You can't see the big picture
from in here, so don't try.

137
00:16:49,221 --> 00:16:50,845
Keep your head down.
Keep it simple.

138
00:16:51,013 --> 00:16:53,170
Just look at what's in front of you.

139
00:16:53,264 --> 00:16:54,377
That's what he said.

140
00:16:55,014 --> 00:16:59,139
Start with us.
We got an escape artist and a cop.

141
00:16:59,390 --> 00:17:00,551
There's gotta be a reason for that.

142
00:17:01,307 --> 00:17:05,171
You're doctor, Holloway. It gives you
a function, a reason, right?

143
00:17:05,933 --> 00:17:07,473
No. It's just makes me go why me

144
00:17:07,558 --> 00:17:10,592
and why not one of the other
10 million doctors out there.

145
00:17:17,351 --> 00:17:19,177
Leaven, what are you?

146
00:17:19,560 --> 00:17:25,807
Nothing. I just go to school.
I hang out with my friends.

147
00:17:25,894 --> 00:17:28,383
- What else?
- There's nothing else.

148
00:17:29,437 --> 00:17:33,218
My parents are these people.
I live with them. I'm boring.

149
00:17:33,604 --> 00:17:37,349
I think we have to ask
the big questions.

150
00:17:37,480 --> 00:17:38,854
What does it want?

151
00:17:38,980 --> 00:17:40,687
What is it thinking?

152
00:17:41,480 --> 00:17:43,104
One down, four to go.

153
00:17:47,898 --> 00:17:50,138
Why don't you tell us
what your purpose is, Worth?

154
00:17:50,357 --> 00:17:51,933
Often wondered that myself.

155
00:17:57,733 --> 00:17:59,013
I'm just a guy.

156
00:17:59,400 --> 00:18:02,399
I work in an office building,
doing office building stuff.

157
00:18:02,942 --> 00:18:07,647
I wasn't exactly bursting with
"joie de vivre" before I got here.

158
00:18:07,735 --> 00:18:09,358
Life just sucks in general.

159
00:18:09,527 --> 00:18:12,893
- I can't stand that attitude.
- Because he's right.

160
00:18:13,653 --> 00:18:15,857
What's your purpose, Quentin?

161
00:18:20,904 --> 00:18:23,475
Kids, three of them.

162
00:18:25,030 --> 00:18:26,487
I haven't made my peace yet.

163
00:18:28,530 --> 00:18:30,521
I'm getting out of here,
no matter what.

164
00:18:30,697 --> 00:18:32,653
That's where
my strength comes from.

165
00:18:33,323 --> 00:18:35,230
You, people,
find yours wherever you got it.

166
00:18:36,698 --> 00:18:38,654
For Christ's sake, Worth.
What do you live for?

167
00:18:38,740 --> 00:18:40,980
Don't you have a wife or
a girlfriend, or something?

168
00:18:41,199 --> 00:18:43,486
No. I've got a pretty fine
collection of pornography.

169
00:18:44,075 --> 00:18:46,279
Oh, nice, nice.

170
00:18:48,075 --> 00:18:51,690
I haven't got anybody either, but
I'm not giving up! I am pissed off.

171
00:18:51,993 --> 00:18:53,367
They came into our homes!

172
00:18:53,701 --> 00:18:57,945
They stripped us bare.
They took my rings, they took...

173
00:18:58,827 --> 00:19:00,865
...oh, my amethyst.

174
00:19:04,703 --> 00:19:06,445
I wanna know who's responsible.

175
00:19:07,537 --> 00:19:10,026
Leaven. Your glasses?

176
00:19:12,371 --> 00:19:13,401
You don't need them?

177
00:19:14,371 --> 00:19:15,485
They're for reading.

178
00:19:18,080 --> 00:19:22,205
Well they took off our jewelry,
but why they put these on you.

179
00:19:23,706 --> 00:19:24,820
If nothing is random,

180
00:19:25,873 --> 00:19:26,952
why are they here?

181
00:19:33,708 --> 00:19:38,615
Leaven. What do you do
in school? Math?

182
00:19:43,877 --> 00:19:45,074
What can they mean?

183
00:19:55,879 --> 00:19:57,158
149.

184
00:20:13,090 --> 00:20:16,787
Prime numbers. I can't believe
I didn't see it before.

185
00:20:17,049 --> 00:20:17,878
See what?

186
00:20:18,174 --> 00:20:20,710
It seems like, if any
of these numbers are prime,

187
00:20:20,841 --> 00:20:21,872
then the room's trapped.

188
00:20:25,509 --> 00:20:29,373
645, 645... That's not prime.

189
00:20:30,176 --> 00:20:32,665
372... no.

190
00:20:34,177 --> 00:20:36,417
649...

191
00:20:37,511 --> 00:20:40,000
Well, 11 times 59.
It's not prime either.

192
00:20:42,470 --> 00:20:43,963
So that room is safe.

193
00:20:44,554 --> 00:20:45,418
Wait.

194
00:20:45,512 --> 00:20:48,760
How can you make that assumption
based on one prime number trap?

195
00:20:48,846 --> 00:20:53,006
I'm not. The incinerator thing
was prime 083.

196
00:20:53,680 --> 00:20:57,177
The molecular chemical thing had
137. The acid room had 149.

197
00:20:57,348 --> 00:20:58,627
You remember all that in your head?

198
00:20:58,848 --> 00:21:00,175
I have a facility for it.

199
00:21:01,015 --> 00:21:05,720
Leaven, you beautiful brain.

200
00:21:07,308 --> 00:21:08,054
Boot it.

201
00:21:12,392 --> 00:21:13,671
Okay, out of the way.

202
00:21:14,017 --> 00:21:15,427
Brains before beauty.

203
00:21:21,852 --> 00:21:24,222
Safe, safe.

204
00:21:26,186 --> 00:21:29,599
Prime numbers! Prime numbers!

205
00:21:38,563 --> 00:21:40,850
Oh, how long have we been in here?

206
00:21:43,064 --> 00:21:44,343
Nine or ten hours.

207
00:21:46,939 --> 00:21:47,852
How do you know?

208
00:21:49,648 --> 00:21:54,057
Five o'clock shadow. Last thing
I remember was shaving.

209
00:21:55,816 --> 00:21:58,649
I guess
I missed breakfast or lunch...

210
00:21:59,317 --> 00:22:00,514
or whatever.

211
00:22:02,901 --> 00:22:05,603
Don't worry.
I'll be home in time for dinner.

212
00:22:08,527 --> 00:22:10,813
If we get out, I'll make you dinner.

213
00:22:12,944 --> 00:22:14,223
You got a date.

214
00:22:33,197 --> 00:22:34,192
Doin' good.

215
00:22:48,950 --> 00:22:52,399
I need to smoke.
I'd smoke a butt off a sidewalk.

216
00:22:53,076 --> 00:22:56,407
Holloway.
Just reel yourself in a bit. Come on.

217
00:22:56,702 --> 00:22:58,360
We're moving along.
Things are looking up.

218
00:22:58,535 --> 00:23:01,699
Ok, ok. You are right.
I quit smoking years ago.

219
00:23:03,536 --> 00:23:04,863
I just need to be occupied.

220
00:23:05,245 --> 00:23:08,611
Talk then. Have a conversation.
What kind of doctor are you anyway?

221
00:23:09,287 --> 00:23:11,029
Oh, you know, the free kind.

222
00:23:15,330 --> 00:23:17,819
Come on. Help me.
Tell me about your rug rats.

223
00:23:19,330 --> 00:23:23,325
We have three boys. 9, 7 and 5.

224
00:23:23,915 --> 00:23:27,743
Good God. Poor woman.
There's no way I'd survive that.

225
00:23:29,624 --> 00:23:30,738
She didn't either.

226
00:23:33,416 --> 00:23:35,703
She's not dead,
we're just separated.

227
00:23:37,709 --> 00:23:40,660
I'm sorry.
I can't just shoot the breeze.

228
00:23:42,626 --> 00:23:44,036
These numbers aren't prime.

229
00:23:44,126 --> 00:23:45,868
Okay, clear.

230
00:23:50,586 --> 00:23:51,913
Excuse me, sorry.

231
00:23:57,712 --> 00:24:00,545
You, could try and
help me out here, buddy.

232
00:24:01,046 --> 00:24:02,124
No, I couldn't.

233
00:24:11,589 --> 00:24:13,248
This one's trapped too.

234
00:24:19,299 --> 00:24:20,840
We have to backtrack?

235
00:24:24,508 --> 00:24:25,587
Not yet.

236
00:24:32,385 --> 00:24:33,415
Read them to me.

237
00:24:47,262 --> 00:24:50,426
- What are you, his coat rack?
- Oh, please!

238
00:25:01,931 --> 00:25:02,962
It's stuck.

239
00:25:05,974 --> 00:25:06,720
Look out.

240
00:25:14,809 --> 00:25:16,266
This room is green.

241
00:25:21,852 --> 00:25:22,930
Holloway?

242
00:25:31,062 --> 00:25:31,891
Hi there.

243
00:25:36,562 --> 00:25:38,221
This room is green.

244
00:25:38,896 --> 00:25:39,809
Yes, it is.

245
00:25:42,105 --> 00:25:44,061
I wanna go back to the blue room.

246
00:25:45,731 --> 00:25:47,058
What is it? Shock or what?

247
00:25:47,648 --> 00:25:49,390
I think he's mentally handicapped.

248
00:25:50,190 --> 00:25:51,564
I like the blue room.

249
00:25:52,982 --> 00:25:56,478
- Jesus Christ.
- He almost broke my neck.

250
00:25:57,191 --> 00:26:01,102
Hey there, are you all alone?
You want to hold my hand, honey?

251
00:26:02,067 --> 00:26:05,515
Butter first, then honey, Kazan.
Butter first, then honey...

252
00:26:05,651 --> 00:26:09,859
- How'd he survive?
- I want to go back to the blue room.

253
00:26:10,235 --> 00:26:12,938
There's lots of blue rooms.
We'll find you another real soon.

254
00:26:14,361 --> 00:26:15,735
This is just way too bizarre.

255
00:26:16,736 --> 00:26:18,941
Well, you just worry
about your numbers then.

256
00:26:21,529 --> 00:26:23,152
Go on. I'll look after him.

257
00:26:27,113 --> 00:26:30,561
Safe. Obviously,
since he almost fell on my head.

258
00:26:30,822 --> 00:26:33,986
Should we go for a walk, Kazan?

259
00:26:35,031 --> 00:26:36,228
You want to go for a walk?

260
00:26:50,617 --> 00:26:52,857
Let's not make him do
the climbing thing right away.

261
00:26:53,076 --> 00:26:53,940
Holloway...

262
00:26:55,076 --> 00:26:56,106
Hol-Io-way.

263
00:27:01,285 --> 00:27:03,691
Could they have taken us
all the way to New Mexico?

264
00:27:03,828 --> 00:27:05,285
What are you
talking about, Holloway?

265
00:27:06,745 --> 00:27:09,281
I'm talking about where do you
hide something this big.

266
00:27:09,995 --> 00:27:11,572
At least he's good for something.

267
00:27:15,830 --> 00:27:17,488
I'm sorry to shake
your foundations, Quentin,

268
00:27:17,622 --> 00:27:19,992
but you have no idea
where your tax dollars go.

269
00:27:20,705 --> 00:27:22,364
Free clinic doctors?

270
00:27:23,081 --> 00:27:25,451
Only the military
industrial complex could afford

271
00:27:25,540 --> 00:27:27,246
to build something this size.

272
00:27:27,373 --> 00:27:30,989
Holloway, what is
the military industrial complex?

273
00:27:31,082 --> 00:27:32,456
Have you ever been there?

274
00:27:32,541 --> 00:27:34,082
I'm telling you,
it's not that complex.

275
00:27:34,208 --> 00:27:35,914
How would you know
from where you are?

276
00:27:37,000 --> 00:27:39,074
Who do you think
the establishment is?

277
00:27:39,167 --> 00:27:40,446
It's just guys like me.

278
00:27:40,834 --> 00:27:43,074
Their desks are bigger,
but their jobs are't.

279
00:27:43,168 --> 00:27:45,123
They don't conspire...
they buy boats.

280
00:27:45,876 --> 00:27:48,828
No, this place is...
remember Scaramanga?

281
00:27:49,710 --> 00:27:51,701
The bad guy in
"The Man With The Golden Gun".

282
00:27:54,045 --> 00:27:56,331
It's some rich
psycho's entertainment.

283
00:27:59,379 --> 00:28:00,540
Is that what you think?

284
00:28:01,629 --> 00:28:02,459
Clear.

285
00:28:13,465 --> 00:28:15,456
Ok. You are a cop.

286
00:28:16,632 --> 00:28:19,630
Single bullet theory. Right on.

287
00:28:30,051 --> 00:28:32,718
- Gas!
- Holloway, get back here!

288
00:28:37,552 --> 00:28:40,965
It's okay.
I just swallowed my button.

289
00:28:45,845 --> 00:28:47,386
I hate this. I hate this.

290
00:28:52,430 --> 00:28:54,634
Your boy is having
a conniption fit in there.

291
00:28:59,139 --> 00:29:01,213
It's like cramming without coffee.

292
00:29:01,556 --> 00:29:03,428
- She needs a break.
- She can do it.

293
00:29:13,392 --> 00:29:14,766
They don't look like prime to me.

294
00:29:15,267 --> 00:29:17,507
Is that your two bits worth, Worth?

295
00:29:18,518 --> 00:29:20,010
For what it's worth.

296
00:29:25,394 --> 00:29:30,597
- Well?
- Well, he's right. Not prime.

297
00:29:35,270 --> 00:29:38,103
Stop! In front of you!

298
00:29:51,773 --> 00:29:52,686
What is it?

299
00:30:02,900 --> 00:30:04,062
Shut up!

300
00:30:07,609 --> 00:30:10,145
I don't know what happened.
It wasn't prime.

301
00:30:12,485 --> 00:30:14,144
Quentin, hold still.

302
00:30:16,986 --> 00:30:21,312
- Somebody stops that racket.
- Worth!

303
00:30:24,404 --> 00:30:25,648
Leave the boots.

304
00:30:35,406 --> 00:30:37,313
And shut the fucking door!

305
00:30:41,365 --> 00:30:43,522
I had a feeling
about that fucking guy.

306
00:30:44,324 --> 00:30:45,865
He knew about that trap.

307
00:30:46,408 --> 00:30:47,735
These numbers aren't prime.

308
00:30:47,825 --> 00:30:49,567
Then your number system failed,
but he knew...

309
00:30:49,742 --> 00:30:51,400
Knew what? How would he know?

310
00:30:51,534 --> 00:30:53,110
You are the paranoid one,
think about it.

311
00:30:53,201 --> 00:30:55,772
His only function so far has been
to kick us when we're down.

312
00:30:55,868 --> 00:30:58,783
So he has a bad attitude. Are you
saying, that makes him a spy?

313
00:30:58,952 --> 00:31:01,571
Trust me on this. It's my job
to read people like an X-Ray.

314
00:31:07,161 --> 00:31:08,441
He doesn't like red rooms.

315
00:31:17,080 --> 00:31:18,110
So what happened?

316
00:31:19,080 --> 00:31:21,201
- You saw what happened.
- Quentin!

317
00:31:21,622 --> 00:31:23,447
I guess the numbers are
more complicated that I thought.

318
00:31:23,998 --> 00:31:25,159
Maybe they mean nothing at all.

319
00:31:25,498 --> 00:31:27,240
No. It means
they are more involved.

320
00:31:27,748 --> 00:31:29,455
They've worked for us up 'till now,
haven't they?

321
00:31:29,540 --> 00:31:31,247
I just need more time with them.

322
00:31:31,540 --> 00:31:33,780
Well, we need to rest anyway.

323
00:31:34,583 --> 00:31:37,830
Well. That's handy. 'Cause there's
not a fuck of a lot else we can do.

324
00:31:50,961 --> 00:31:52,868
Are they telling you anything?

325
00:31:54,003 --> 00:31:55,412
They're not tarot cards.

326
00:31:57,712 --> 00:32:00,461
Do you have any idea how many
variables I have to consider

327
00:32:00,545 --> 00:32:03,165
before I can
decipher numbers this size?

328
00:32:04,004 --> 00:32:05,912
They don't reveal
themselves right away.

329
00:32:07,172 --> 00:32:08,285
They're like people.

330
00:32:15,006 --> 00:32:16,748
Oh, gross.

331
00:32:20,049 --> 00:32:23,000
Oh, not here honey.
Over in the corner.

332
00:32:30,176 --> 00:32:31,882
Well, he's just peeing.

333
00:32:32,968 --> 00:32:34,461
Jesus Christ.

334
00:32:35,260 --> 00:32:38,045
That's excellent.
Now it totally reeks in here!

335
00:32:40,469 --> 00:32:42,211
You find this all
pretty funny, don't you?

336
00:32:47,845 --> 00:32:49,753
What's your
fucking problem, Worth?

337
00:32:51,471 --> 00:32:53,427
Even Holloway's
holding up better than you.

338
00:32:54,138 --> 00:32:58,215
Get over there and help her with him.
That's your job. Babysitter.

339
00:33:00,556 --> 00:33:02,097
Jawohl, Kommandant.

340
00:33:05,057 --> 00:33:07,380
Somebody has to take
responsability around here.

341
00:33:08,015 --> 00:33:10,137
And that somebody has to be you.

342
00:33:10,391 --> 00:33:12,263
Not all of us have
the luxury of playing nihilist.

343
00:33:12,766 --> 00:33:15,599
Not all of us are
conceited enough to play hero.

344
00:33:17,600 --> 00:33:19,342
This is a will to live.

345
00:33:19,559 --> 00:33:21,182
Everybody's got it,
Worth, even you.

346
00:33:21,309 --> 00:33:23,633
Especially you,
hiding behind that cynical front.

347
00:33:24,185 --> 00:33:25,180
A will to live.

348
00:33:25,644 --> 00:33:28,215
That's the warm,
cosy feeling deep inside.

349
00:33:28,769 --> 00:33:30,725
Thanks Quentin, I'm a new man.

350
00:33:30,978 --> 00:33:34,426
Oh, poor Worth. Nobody loves me.

351
00:33:34,895 --> 00:33:36,353
If that's the chip
on your shoulder, why

352
00:33:36,479 --> 00:33:37,557
did you lug it all this way?

353
00:33:37,854 --> 00:33:39,430
Why didn't you
just lie down and die?

354
00:33:53,440 --> 00:33:54,470
Do it.

355
00:33:54,982 --> 00:33:57,731
Show us you have some backbone
and jump in the sushi machine.

356
00:33:58,107 --> 00:33:59,269
Be a man.

357
00:34:08,818 --> 00:34:10,015
Thought so.

358
00:34:12,777 --> 00:34:14,234
Fuck you Quentin!

359
00:34:16,861 --> 00:34:19,314
I don't wanna die.
I'm just being realistic.

360
00:34:19,403 --> 00:34:21,228
Do you think they'd go to all
the trouble to build this thing

361
00:34:21,320 --> 00:34:22,434
if we could just walk out?

362
00:34:22,528 --> 00:34:23,690
Do you think
they would have left us clues

363
00:34:23,779 --> 00:34:25,816
and let us beat it so far
if there wasn't a way out?

364
00:34:25,904 --> 00:34:27,183
You think we matter? We don't.

365
00:34:27,279 --> 00:34:29,946
Put us out of your misery so we can
get on with getting out of here.

366
00:34:30,030 --> 00:34:31,404
You're not getting out of here!

367
00:34:31,488 --> 00:34:33,029
- Yes, we are!
- No, you're not!

368
00:34:33,114 --> 00:34:36,195
- Yes, we are!
- There is no way out of here!

369
00:34:51,783 --> 00:34:52,981
Gotchya.

370
00:34:59,243 --> 00:35:03,024
How do you know that?

371
00:35:05,619 --> 00:35:07,112
Answer the question, Worth.

372
00:35:09,120 --> 00:35:11,360
Oh, god.

373
00:35:16,246 --> 00:35:17,408
Who are you?

374
00:35:28,790 --> 00:35:30,247
I'm the poison.

375
00:35:32,791 --> 00:35:34,331
I designed the outer shell.

376
00:35:35,249 --> 00:35:36,328
The what?

377
00:35:37,500 --> 00:35:39,407
The shell. The sarcophagus.

378
00:35:40,750 --> 00:35:42,243
You built this thing?

379
00:35:42,334 --> 00:35:43,613
Not this part. The exterior.

380
00:35:43,751 --> 00:35:46,500
I don't know anything about the
numbers or anything else in here.

381
00:35:47,501 --> 00:35:51,163
I was contracted to draw
plans for a hollow shell.

382
00:35:52,669 --> 00:35:53,783
A cube.

383
00:35:54,669 --> 00:35:57,537
A cube? Why didn't you tell us?

384
00:35:58,628 --> 00:36:01,662
For God's sake, Worth,
you knew what it was.

385
00:36:03,587 --> 00:36:04,749
No.

386
00:36:05,671 --> 00:36:08,504
Worth. You're lying.

387
00:36:12,547 --> 00:36:13,957
Was not at first.

388
00:36:14,839 --> 00:36:16,119
Who's behind it?

389
00:36:20,174 --> 00:36:21,169
I don't know.

390
00:36:21,882 --> 00:36:23,257
Who hired you?

391
00:36:25,216 --> 00:36:26,247
I didn't ask.

392
00:36:28,633 --> 00:36:30,292
I never even left my office.

393
00:36:31,092 --> 00:36:33,416
I talked on the phone to some
people, other guys like me.

394
00:36:33,593 --> 00:36:35,667
Specialists,
working on small details.

395
00:36:35,843 --> 00:36:37,122
Nobody knew what it was.

396
00:36:37,843 --> 00:36:38,957
Nobody cared.

397
00:36:39,177 --> 00:36:41,880
Bullshit.
You knew from square one.

398
00:36:42,761 --> 00:36:45,843
Look at him. He is up
to his eyeballs in this thing.

399
00:36:45,970 --> 00:36:49,217
No, Quentin.
That's how they stay hidden.

400
00:36:49,762 --> 00:36:50,876
You keep everyone separated

401
00:36:50,971 --> 00:36:53,424
so the left hand doesn't know
what the right hand is doing.

402
00:36:53,554 --> 00:36:55,711
The brain
never comes out in the open.

403
00:36:56,680 --> 00:36:57,758
Whose brain?

404
00:36:59,305 --> 00:37:01,545
It's all the same machine, right!

405
00:37:01,681 --> 00:37:05,462
The Pentagone, multinational
corporations, the police.

406
00:37:06,098 --> 00:37:09,927
If you do one little job,
you build a widget in Saskatoon,

407
00:37:10,057 --> 00:37:12,428
and the next thing you know
it's two miles under

408
00:37:12,558 --> 00:37:15,722
the desert, the essential
component of a death machine.

409
00:37:16,433 --> 00:37:19,349
I was right.
All along, my whole life,

410
00:37:19,476 --> 00:37:21,762
I knew it. I told you, Quentin.

411
00:37:21,893 --> 00:37:24,346
Nobody's every gonna
call me paranoid again.

412
00:37:24,518 --> 00:37:27,433
We gotta get out of here and
blow the lid of this thing!

413
00:37:33,811 --> 00:37:35,886
Holloway, you don't get it.

414
00:37:36,729 --> 00:37:39,134
Then help me,
please, I need to know.

415
00:37:40,604 --> 00:37:42,311
This may be hard
for you to understand,

416
00:37:42,396 --> 00:37:44,138
but there's no conspiracy.

417
00:37:44,605 --> 00:37:46,062
Nobody is in charge.

418
00:37:46,605 --> 00:37:51,098
It's a headless blunder operating
under the illusion of a master plan.

419
00:37:51,439 --> 00:37:52,553
Can you grasp that?

420
00:37:53,023 --> 00:37:55,097
Big brother is not watching you.

421
00:37:57,566 --> 00:37:59,556
What kind of
fuckin' explanation is that?

422
00:37:59,691 --> 00:38:00,935
It's the best you are gonna get.

423
00:38:01,024 --> 00:38:02,850
I looked, and the only conclusion
I could come to is that

424
00:38:03,025 --> 00:38:04,434
there is nobody up there.

425
00:38:04,567 --> 00:38:06,688
Somebody had to say
yes to this thing.

426
00:38:06,775 --> 00:38:08,683
What thing?
Only we know what it is.

427
00:38:08,776 --> 00:38:11,893
- We have no idea what it is.
- We know more than anybody else.

428
00:38:12,318 --> 00:38:14,356
I mean, somebody might have
known sometime before they go,

429
00:38:14,443 --> 00:38:16,979
they got fired, or
voted out, or sold it,

430
00:38:17,361 --> 00:38:18,984
but if this place
ever had a purpose,

431
00:38:19,069 --> 00:38:21,558
and it got miscommunicated,
or lost in a shuffle.

432
00:38:21,903 --> 00:38:23,230
I mean, this is and accident,

433
00:38:23,320 --> 00:38:26,733
a forgotten perpetual
public works project.

434
00:38:26,987 --> 00:38:28,646
Do you think anybody
wants to ask questions?

435
00:38:28,904 --> 00:38:31,025
All they want is
a clear conscience,

436
00:38:31,155 --> 00:38:32,399
and a fat paycheck.

437
00:38:32,780 --> 00:38:34,486
I leaned on my shovel
for months on this one.

438
00:38:34,614 --> 00:38:35,988
This was a great job!

439
00:38:38,406 --> 00:38:39,947
Why put people in it?

440
00:38:40,990 --> 00:38:45,031
Because it's here. You have
to use it or you admit it's pointless.

441
00:38:45,157 --> 00:38:47,314
But it is pointless.

442
00:38:49,033 --> 00:38:50,988
Quentin. That's my point.

443
00:38:52,450 --> 00:38:54,157
What have we come to?

444
00:38:55,701 --> 00:38:57,857
It's so much worse than I thought.

445
00:38:59,076 --> 00:39:01,909
Not really. Just more pathetic.

446
00:39:02,868 --> 00:39:04,990
You make me sick, Worth.

447
00:39:05,411 --> 00:39:07,117
I make me sick too.

448
00:39:07,994 --> 00:39:09,487
We're both part of the system.

449
00:39:10,078 --> 00:39:13,574
I drew a box, you walk a beat.
It's like you said, Quentin,

450
00:39:13,704 --> 00:39:15,576
is keep your head down,
keep it simple,

451
00:39:15,704 --> 00:39:17,114
just look at what's in front of you.

452
00:39:17,246 --> 00:39:19,036
I mean, nobody wants to see
the big picture.

453
00:39:19,288 --> 00:39:20,567
Life's too complicated.

454
00:39:21,372 --> 00:39:26,409
I mean, let's face it, the reason
we're here is that it's out of control.

455
00:39:39,000 --> 00:39:40,991
This is how we ruin the world?

456
00:39:41,709 --> 00:39:46,082
Well, have you been on glue
all your lives?

457
00:39:46,709 --> 00:39:50,241
I've felt guilty for ruining
the world since I was like 7.

458
00:39:51,294 --> 00:39:54,909
God, if you need someone
to blame, throw a rock.

459
00:40:02,170 --> 00:40:03,332
Well, I feel better.

460
00:40:04,712 --> 00:40:06,336
That's why you stayed with us.

461
00:40:07,755 --> 00:40:09,034
To confess.

462
00:40:23,716 --> 00:40:26,335
You still looking
for someone to bust, Quentin?

463
00:40:36,426 --> 00:40:38,417
Quentin! Stop it! Stop it!

464
00:40:40,219 --> 00:40:41,416
We need him.

465
00:40:43,969 --> 00:40:44,964
What for?

466
00:40:45,219 --> 00:40:47,175
Have you gone absolutely mad?

467
00:40:47,303 --> 00:40:49,709
He's the only one who knows
anything about the place.

468
00:41:02,014 --> 00:41:05,012
- Worth.
- Hi.

469
00:41:05,806 --> 00:41:08,758
- So there's this outer shell.
- Yeah.

470
00:41:08,932 --> 00:41:12,796
- And it's a cube, right? Like this.
- I assume so.

471
00:41:13,016 --> 00:41:15,719
- Are there any doors?
- There's one door.

472
00:41:15,808 --> 00:41:18,214
- Where?
- Wherever the door guy put it.

473
00:41:18,850 --> 00:41:21,470
Six guesses, and
it's sealed from the outside.

474
00:41:22,476 --> 00:41:25,510
And, what are the dimensions
of the outer shell?

475
00:41:27,560 --> 00:41:29,551
434 square feet.

476
00:41:39,396 --> 00:41:40,474
May I?

477
00:41:40,562 --> 00:41:42,435
Come on, honey, slide over.

478
00:41:48,272 --> 00:41:50,559
14 by 14 by 14.

479
00:41:50,814 --> 00:41:53,896
The inner cube can't be flush
with the shell wall, there's a space.

480
00:41:54,606 --> 00:41:55,519
One cube?

481
00:41:55,898 --> 00:41:57,308
I don't know, it makes sense.

482
00:41:58,691 --> 00:42:04,107
Ok. The biggest the cube
can be then is...

483
00:42:04,817 --> 00:42:08,230
26 rooms high,
26 rooms across, so...

484
00:42:08,692 --> 00:42:11,098
17.576 rooms.

485
00:42:11,609 --> 00:42:15,307
Seventeen thousand, five hundred
and seventy-six rooms?

486
00:42:17,902 --> 00:42:19,360
That makes me queasy.

487
00:42:23,403 --> 00:42:24,517
Descartes!

488
00:42:27,237 --> 00:42:30,485
- Leaven, you are a genius.
- What? What?

489
00:42:31,154 --> 00:42:35,315
Cartesian coordinates. Of course,
coded cartesian coordinates.

490
00:42:35,614 --> 00:42:38,565
They're used in geometry to plot
points on a 3-dimensional graph.

491
00:42:38,989 --> 00:42:40,814
In English, slower.

492
00:42:41,490 --> 00:42:44,737
Bonjour?
These numbers are markers,

493
00:42:44,990 --> 00:42:47,905
and grid reference, like latitude
and longitude on a map.

494
00:42:48,241 --> 00:42:51,026
The numbers tell us where
we are inside the cube.

495
00:42:51,158 --> 00:42:52,532
Well, where are we?

496
00:42:56,367 --> 00:42:57,232
It works.

497
00:42:57,492 --> 00:43:01,321
Okay. All I have to do is add
the numbers together.

498
00:43:01,951 --> 00:43:03,741
The X coordinate is 19...

499
00:43:04,369 --> 00:43:08,363
Y is 26 rooms...

500
00:43:09,703 --> 00:43:11,196
So that places us...

501
00:43:14,204 --> 00:43:15,827
...seven rooms from the edge.

502
00:43:16,204 --> 00:43:18,361
All right, let's go.

503
00:43:18,746 --> 00:43:22,610
Just out of curiosity, I mean,
don't hit me again, or anything...

504
00:43:22,747 --> 00:43:23,944
but what are you gonna do
when you get there?

505
00:43:24,039 --> 00:43:25,579
Maybe we can get the door open.

506
00:43:26,997 --> 00:43:30,328
What we need is to do figure out
how to get around the traps.

507
00:43:30,415 --> 00:43:31,659
I'm dealing with that Holloway.

508
00:43:31,748 --> 00:43:33,325
I'm looking for
practical solutions here.

509
00:43:33,665 --> 00:43:35,656
Well, you haven't found any yet.

510
00:43:39,250 --> 00:43:43,789
We cut the risk with the numbers
and the boot. Worth will go in first.

511
00:43:43,875 --> 00:43:46,660
No, he won't Quentin!
We take turns!

512
00:43:47,959 --> 00:43:48,907
Relax.

513
00:43:57,503 --> 00:43:58,616
Room for two in there?

514
00:44:05,004 --> 00:44:06,118
What's the matter?

515
00:44:06,588 --> 00:44:09,954
These coordinates. 14, 27, 14.

516
00:44:10,588 --> 00:44:12,875
- What about 'em?
- They don't make sense.

517
00:44:13,339 --> 00:44:15,330
Assuming the cube is
26 rooms across,

518
00:44:15,464 --> 00:44:17,372
there can't be
a coordinate larger than 26.

519
00:44:17,965 --> 00:44:20,205
If this were right, then
we would be outside of the cube.

520
00:44:23,174 --> 00:44:25,295
No, not outside of the cube.

521
00:44:27,258 --> 00:44:29,000
I guess that means
we're not having dinner.

522
00:44:29,800 --> 00:44:36,129
Trap. Trap. Trap. Trap.

523
00:44:38,385 --> 00:44:39,546
Trap!

524
00:44:47,053 --> 00:44:48,215
Trap!

525
00:44:53,512 --> 00:44:54,709
Sound activated.

526
00:45:11,140 --> 00:45:12,089
Lovely.

527
00:45:13,391 --> 00:45:15,962
How come the sound of the door
opening didn't set it off?

528
00:45:16,558 --> 00:45:18,016
Must be rigged to ignore it.

529
00:45:18,100 --> 00:45:20,803
So that's it. The edge is
surrounded by traps.

530
00:45:20,934 --> 00:45:24,596
Well, I guess we have to backtrack,
and try somewhere else.

531
00:45:24,726 --> 00:45:26,883
Who knows how many detours
we'll have to take.

532
00:45:27,518 --> 00:45:29,260
I say we cross the bitch.

533
00:45:29,644 --> 00:45:30,971
Right!

534
00:45:32,019 --> 00:45:34,140
How many boots do we have left,
Holloway?

535
00:45:38,395 --> 00:45:39,592
Get it off him.

536
00:45:40,604 --> 00:45:42,760
We know how it works.
We just have to be quiet.

537
00:45:43,063 --> 00:45:44,639
That's pretty fucking quiet.

538
00:45:44,938 --> 00:45:48,470
I'm glad you're on side,
Worth, 'cause... you're up.

539
00:45:50,064 --> 00:45:51,261
And he is not coming.

540
00:45:51,731 --> 00:45:53,140
Of course, he is.

541
00:45:53,231 --> 00:45:56,348
- No way.
- We are not leaving him behind.

542
00:45:56,482 --> 00:45:57,595
He's unpredictable.

543
00:45:57,982 --> 00:45:59,523
When we get to the edge,
we can come back for him.

544
00:45:59,607 --> 00:46:01,349
But he'll get somebody killed here.

545
00:46:01,691 --> 00:46:02,721
Am I right?

546
00:46:04,900 --> 00:46:06,097
Shame on you.

547
00:46:06,942 --> 00:46:08,814
Will you look at yourselves?

548
00:46:10,067 --> 00:46:11,608
What have you turned into?

549
00:46:12,026 --> 00:46:16,103
They may have taken our lives away,
but we are still human beings.

550
00:46:17,110 --> 00:46:18,817
That's all we've got left.

551
00:46:21,236 --> 00:46:22,646
We'll come back for him.

552
00:46:24,153 --> 00:46:26,191
That's a lie and you know it.

553
00:46:36,405 --> 00:46:37,400
He'll be quiet.

554
00:49:13,391 --> 00:49:15,962
- What are you doing?
- I'm gonna wait for him.

555
00:49:16,558 --> 00:49:18,383
- No.
- You go out, I'm here.

556
00:49:18,725 --> 00:49:19,755
Okay.

557
00:49:31,394 --> 00:49:32,507
This way.

558
00:51:17,245 --> 00:51:19,948
- You fucking fuck!
- That's enough!

559
00:51:20,038 --> 00:51:22,705
- He is a trap!
- Let him go right now!

560
00:51:22,788 --> 00:51:25,407
The law of the jungle!
He is endangering the pack!

561
00:51:25,580 --> 00:51:27,654
Let him go, you Nazi!

562
00:51:29,998 --> 00:51:31,159
What did you call me?

563
00:51:31,331 --> 00:51:34,081
Quentin, you let
that innocent boy go.

564
00:51:36,165 --> 00:51:38,037
You listen to me, woman.

565
00:51:38,791 --> 00:51:41,873
Everyday I mop up
after your bleeding heart.

566
00:51:42,500 --> 00:51:46,281
The only reason you
even exist is because I keep you.

567
00:51:47,417 --> 00:51:48,661
I know your type,

568
00:51:49,543 --> 00:51:52,873
no kids, no man to fuck you.

569
00:51:53,418 --> 00:51:55,125
So you go around outraged,

570
00:51:55,460 --> 00:51:57,784
sticking your nose up
other people's assholes,

571
00:51:57,877 --> 00:51:59,418
sniffing their business!!!

572
00:52:01,670 --> 00:52:03,577
You missed your boat, Holloway.

573
00:52:06,671 --> 00:52:09,124
You're all dried up
inside there, aren't you?

574
00:52:09,796 --> 00:52:11,503
That's your fucking problem.

575
00:52:12,338 --> 00:52:14,625
How dare you say that to her?

576
00:52:15,755 --> 00:52:18,920
You don't know her, Quentin.
None of us know each other here.

577
00:52:19,048 --> 00:52:22,496
- Oh, I do.
- No you don't.

578
00:52:22,882 --> 00:52:25,287
No wonder your wife left you.

579
00:52:27,132 --> 00:52:30,415
All that bottled up anger.

580
00:52:32,467 --> 00:52:34,707
And a thing for young girls.

581
00:52:45,052 --> 00:52:46,629
God help you, Quentin.

582
00:52:48,636 --> 00:52:50,793
Did you smack
your kids around too?

583
00:53:05,306 --> 00:53:09,964
Is anybody besides me interested in
what's on the other side of that door?

584
00:53:13,140 --> 00:53:14,135
Open it.

585
00:53:21,767 --> 00:53:25,014
Door number six? Not number one?
Door number two?

586
00:53:26,809 --> 00:53:28,302
Open the fuckin' thing.

587
00:53:30,810 --> 00:53:34,508
Oh, sunshine.

588
00:54:00,315 --> 00:54:01,346
Night time.

589
00:54:02,232 --> 00:54:04,058
My old friend, the shell.

590
00:54:06,608 --> 00:54:09,606
It's there. Morning!

591
00:54:13,151 --> 00:54:14,015
Hang on to me.

592
00:54:22,694 --> 00:54:23,891
I can't see shit.

593
00:54:26,361 --> 00:54:27,558
Nothin' to hang on to.

594
00:54:32,946 --> 00:54:34,024
We gotta try something.

595
00:54:34,654 --> 00:54:36,147
We gotta see
if the door's over there.

596
00:54:37,863 --> 00:54:39,689
Someone has to swing
over there, and take a look.

597
00:54:40,030 --> 00:54:40,895
Swing?

598
00:54:42,906 --> 00:54:45,395
We make a rope,
out of clothes.

599
00:54:46,573 --> 00:54:48,280
Take 'em off.
I'll tie it around myself.

600
00:54:48,990 --> 00:54:50,234
Ah, yeah, and you're gonna go.

601
00:54:50,491 --> 00:54:52,861
You weight like 500 ponds,
it'll snap in two seconds.

602
00:54:53,824 --> 00:54:54,855
I'm the lightest.

603
00:54:55,658 --> 00:54:56,523
Forget it.

604
00:54:57,158 --> 00:54:58,153
I'll go.

605
00:54:59,450 --> 00:55:00,730
I'm going, Holloway.

606
00:55:01,367 --> 00:55:03,524
She's right Quentin,
you're too heavy.

607
00:55:03,868 --> 00:55:05,526
I'm the lightest after Leaven.

608
00:55:06,410 --> 00:55:07,986
Anyway, it's my turn.

609
00:55:14,536 --> 00:55:17,488
How long did you know
people were being put in here?

610
00:55:18,412 --> 00:55:19,691
A couple of months.

611
00:55:20,454 --> 00:55:21,733
That's not long,

612
00:55:22,204 --> 00:55:23,697
if you consider your whole life.

613
00:55:24,663 --> 00:55:25,611
I am.

614
00:55:26,872 --> 00:55:29,028
You opened my eyes Worht.
That's something.

615
00:55:31,414 --> 00:55:32,244
David.

616
00:55:34,456 --> 00:55:35,286
Helen.

617
00:55:38,666 --> 00:55:40,075
You're such a Helen.

618
00:56:28,341 --> 00:56:29,999
That's as far as you go.

619
00:56:34,634 --> 00:56:36,174
There's nothing down here.

620
00:56:38,092 --> 00:56:39,087
Hold tight.

621
00:56:40,301 --> 00:56:41,842
I try swinging over there.

622
00:56:51,428 --> 00:56:53,218
Brace yourselves,
I'm gonna try again.

623
00:56:59,346 --> 00:57:04,549
- Okay, one more time.
- Hurry, you're getting heavy.

624
00:57:15,932 --> 00:57:17,758
What the hell's going on?

625
00:57:18,266 --> 00:57:19,889
Get up here now!

626
00:57:52,480 --> 00:57:54,057
- Quentin!
- Have you got her?

627
00:57:54,689 --> 00:57:58,600
- What's going on?
- Quentin, is she okay?

628
00:58:24,819 --> 00:58:29,027
She... slipped.

629
00:58:30,529 --> 00:58:31,559
Holloway?

630
00:59:03,326 --> 00:59:04,949
Hey, shhh...
Come on, Kazan.

631
00:59:06,952 --> 00:59:08,907
Kazan, will you please
stop doing that?

632
00:59:09,869 --> 00:59:13,614
Leaven, you got be strong,
sweetheart.

633
00:59:13,744 --> 00:59:15,072
Don't even talk to me.

634
00:59:17,578 --> 00:59:19,155
We gotta get down to the bottom.

635
00:59:21,412 --> 00:59:23,652
It will be easier to get on
to the shell from there.

636
00:59:25,705 --> 00:59:28,194
It's a long fucking way
with only one boot.

637
00:59:28,539 --> 00:59:30,862
But we gotta do it
before we get too weak.

638
00:59:32,456 --> 00:59:34,364
You gotta keep
cracking the numbers, Leaven.

639
00:59:35,706 --> 00:59:37,283
I can't think anymore.

640
00:59:37,415 --> 00:59:40,414
Sure you can. It's your gift.

641
00:59:40,999 --> 00:59:44,081
It's not a gift. It's just a brain.

642
00:59:45,250 --> 00:59:48,284
Let her sleep for a while. We haven't
slept in fuck knows how long.

643
00:59:49,834 --> 00:59:50,996
All right.

644
00:59:52,626 --> 00:59:53,704
One hour.

645
00:59:54,501 --> 00:59:56,872
How the fuck are you gonna know
how long an hour is?

646
00:59:58,710 --> 01:00:01,246
An hour is as long as I say.

647
01:01:06,222 --> 01:01:07,502
What are you doing?

648
01:01:09,723 --> 01:01:11,132
We have to make it down
to the bottom.

649
01:01:11,515 --> 01:01:13,387
It'll be quiet there, and
you can concentrate.

650
01:01:15,057 --> 01:01:17,593
- You just want to leave them?
- They're traps, Leaven.

651
01:01:18,849 --> 01:01:19,928
We are the key.

652
01:01:20,350 --> 01:01:22,803
I'll get us down there.
You think us out.

653
01:01:23,350 --> 01:01:24,380
Believe in me!

654
01:01:24,809 --> 01:01:27,594
Try and see what I see,
how my mind works.

655
01:01:27,726 --> 01:01:30,559
The flash when I look into someone's
head like a fucking X-ray.

656
01:01:34,227 --> 01:01:35,471
I looked through the walls.

657
01:01:36,352 --> 01:01:40,394
I dreamed him at his desk,
designing everything.

658
01:01:43,020 --> 01:01:44,727
He can't let you solve the puzzle,
see, 'cause

659
01:01:44,812 --> 01:01:46,056
there is a purpose.

660
01:01:46,604 --> 01:01:48,062
We are the purpose. The cube...

661
01:01:48,938 --> 01:01:50,016
...is us.

662
01:01:51,730 --> 01:01:54,894
- Quentin.
- We fit. Like numbers.

663
01:01:56,522 --> 01:01:59,474
A man and a woman.
Two halves of the equation.

664
01:02:00,773 --> 01:02:04,388
I take you down, the perfect key.

665
01:02:05,024 --> 01:02:06,434
I slip you in the lock.

666
01:02:11,858 --> 01:02:15,141
Leaven, it's time to go down.

667
01:02:29,945 --> 01:02:30,975
Get away from her.

668
01:02:33,195 --> 01:02:35,898
Leaven, they're fuckin' spies.

669
01:02:36,196 --> 01:02:37,523
Him, the retard.

670
01:02:38,113 --> 01:02:40,732
Holloway, had outside
information about my family...

671
01:02:40,822 --> 01:02:43,737
but she slipped up, didn't she?
She crossed the line!

672
01:02:46,489 --> 01:02:48,113
You dropped her.

673
01:02:51,990 --> 01:02:53,152
Just go, Quentin.

674
01:02:54,699 --> 01:02:56,856
Give us the boot, you pig!

675
01:03:15,995 --> 01:03:17,571
You don't want the boot.

676
01:03:38,498 --> 01:03:41,912
You want to came with us, Worth?
Down the hatch.

677
01:03:49,834 --> 01:03:51,161
What the fuck's with him?

678
01:04:39,342 --> 01:04:40,539
How did...

679
01:04:42,426 --> 01:04:47,333
It's, it's, it's the Wren.
It's the old Wrenster.

680
01:04:49,261 --> 01:04:50,505
How could...

681
01:04:51,428 --> 01:04:53,751
We've been going around in circles.

682
01:04:54,762 --> 01:04:55,792
That can't be.

683
01:05:00,263 --> 01:05:02,337
- Where are we?
- I don't know!

684
01:05:04,347 --> 01:05:06,633
Where are we?

685
01:05:12,098 --> 01:05:13,342
You figure it out!

686
01:05:13,557 --> 01:05:17,219
You haven't done anything.
All you do is freak out you,

687
01:05:17,807 --> 01:05:19,135
murderer!

688
01:06:01,356 --> 01:06:03,015
I guess you were right, Worth.

689
01:06:04,274 --> 01:06:06,016
There is no way out of here.

690
01:06:32,612 --> 01:06:34,105
Get away from me.

691
01:07:09,160 --> 01:07:10,818
Wasn't Rennes killed in that room?

692
01:07:21,954 --> 01:07:23,530
How come there's nothing out there?

693
01:07:26,246 --> 01:07:27,408
It's the edge.

694
01:07:27,621 --> 01:07:30,324
We weren't at the edge before.
Where's the room that killed Rennes?

695
01:07:31,414 --> 01:07:32,611
Fuck off!

696
01:07:37,290 --> 01:07:38,617
Oh, that was good.

697
01:07:39,332 --> 01:07:42,947
What difference does it make?
We're dead anyways.

698
01:07:43,124 --> 01:07:47,663
Hey, listen to what I'm saying.
There was a room there before.

699
01:07:50,000 --> 01:07:53,082
We haven't been moving in circles.
The rooms have.

700
01:07:53,459 --> 01:07:55,948
- Of course.
- The rooms?

701
01:07:56,293 --> 01:07:58,000
That explains
the thunder and the shaking.

702
01:07:58,127 --> 01:07:59,833
We've been shifting the whole time.

703
01:08:01,919 --> 01:08:04,373
It's the only logical explanation.

704
01:08:07,087 --> 01:08:08,793
I'm such an idiot!

705
01:08:09,629 --> 01:08:12,082
- What are you on to, Leaven?
- Give me a minute.

706
01:08:14,880 --> 01:08:17,415
The numbers are markers,
points on a map, right?

707
01:08:17,922 --> 01:08:18,786
Right.

708
01:08:20,005 --> 01:08:23,253
How do you map a point
that keeps moving?

709
01:08:26,465 --> 01:08:27,744
Permutations.

710
01:08:30,257 --> 01:08:31,252
Permu what?

711
01:08:32,383 --> 01:08:33,413
Permutations.

712
01:08:33,508 --> 01:08:36,175
A list of all the coordinates
that the room passes through.

713
01:08:36,258 --> 01:08:38,130
Like a map, that tells you
where the rooms starts,

714
01:08:38,217 --> 01:08:40,587
how many times it moves,
and where it moves to.

715
01:08:41,801 --> 01:08:43,459
The numbers tell you all that?

716
01:08:43,968 --> 01:08:45,591
I don't know,

717
01:08:45,677 --> 01:08:47,549
see, I've only been looking
at one point on the map,

718
01:08:47,635 --> 01:08:49,673
which is probably
the starting position.

719
01:08:50,344 --> 01:08:53,793
All I saw was what the cube looked
like before it started to move.

720
01:08:54,053 --> 01:08:55,380
Okay, so it's moving.

721
01:08:58,804 --> 01:09:00,048
How do we get out?

722
01:09:02,596 --> 01:09:03,876
27.

723
01:09:08,264 --> 01:09:10,006
I know where the exit is.

724
01:09:11,348 --> 01:09:12,260
Where?

725
01:09:13,098 --> 01:09:15,421
- Stay away from me.
- Back off, Quentin.

726
01:09:16,599 --> 01:09:17,878
I just wanna know.

727
01:09:19,141 --> 01:09:20,468
Don't you wanna know?

728
01:09:24,517 --> 01:09:26,721
You remember that room
we passed through before,

729
01:09:26,975 --> 01:09:29,262
the one with the coordinate
larger than 26?

730
01:09:29,726 --> 01:09:30,756
What about it?

731
01:09:31,851 --> 01:09:35,928
That coordinate placed the room
outside the cube.

732
01:09:38,602 --> 01:09:39,515
A bridge.

733
01:09:40,019 --> 01:09:43,432
Right.
But only in its original position.

734
01:09:45,062 --> 01:09:46,341
What are you talking about?

735
01:09:50,229 --> 01:09:53,430
Look.
The room starts off as a bridge,

736
01:09:53,522 --> 01:09:55,559
and then it moves its way
through the maze,

737
01:09:55,647 --> 01:09:57,104
which is where we ran into it.

738
01:09:57,481 --> 01:10:00,562
But at some point,
it must return to its original position.

739
01:10:00,648 --> 01:10:03,646
- So a bridge is only a bridge.
- For a short period of time.

740
01:10:04,107 --> 01:10:06,678
This thing is like
a giant combination lock.

741
01:10:06,774 --> 01:10:09,179
When the rooms are in their
starting position, the lock is open.

742
01:10:09,274 --> 01:10:11,763
But when they move
out of alignment, the lock closes.

743
01:10:11,941 --> 01:10:13,849
With a structure this size,
it must take days

744
01:10:13,942 --> 01:10:15,814
for the rooms
to complete a full cycle.

745
01:10:16,359 --> 01:10:17,733
So, when does it open?

746
01:10:27,277 --> 01:10:28,308
Don't.

747
01:10:28,944 --> 01:10:31,433
To find the original coordinates,
the numbers are added together.

748
01:10:31,528 --> 01:10:34,278
To find the permutations, they're
subtracted from one another.

749
01:10:37,529 --> 01:10:38,193
That's it!

750
01:10:39,321 --> 01:10:42,853
This room moves to zero,
1 and -1 on the X-axis.

751
01:10:42,988 --> 01:10:45,026
2, 5 and -7 on Y.

752
01:10:45,656 --> 01:10:48,488
And 1, and -1 and zero on Z.

753
01:10:48,698 --> 01:10:50,155
And what does that mean?

754
01:10:50,865 --> 01:10:52,144
You suck at math?

755
01:10:52,657 --> 01:10:55,228
Okay, I need the room numbers
around us as reference points.

756
01:10:57,658 --> 01:11:01,604
666, 897, 466.

757
01:11:03,617 --> 01:11:08,358
- 567, 898. Okay?
- Yes.

758
01:11:08,451 --> 01:11:11,615
And 545.
Did you get that?

759
01:11:15,661 --> 01:11:19,904
656, 778, 462.

760
01:11:21,328 --> 01:11:25,572
That's enough.
X is 17, Y is 25 and Z is 14.

761
01:11:28,830 --> 01:11:31,117
Which means
this room makes 2 more moves

762
01:11:31,205 --> 01:11:33,243
before returning
to its original position.

763
01:11:33,330 --> 01:11:35,203
- Do we have time?
- Maybe.

764
01:11:35,331 --> 01:11:36,160
Then let's go!

765
01:11:36,456 --> 01:11:37,866
Can you work
the traps into this system?

766
01:11:37,956 --> 01:11:39,947
Fuck the traps.
Let's get to the bridge.

767
01:11:40,040 --> 01:11:42,494
You threw out our last boot,
you fucking idiot.

768
01:11:42,582 --> 01:11:45,450
- Technically, I can identify the traps.
- Technically?

769
01:11:45,583 --> 01:11:47,076
At first, I thought
that they were identified

770
01:11:47,166 --> 01:11:48,908
by prime numbers,
but they are not.

771
01:11:49,000 --> 01:11:51,453
They are identified by numbers
that are the power of a prime.

772
01:11:51,542 --> 01:11:53,450
- Ok, so?
- Can you calculate that?

773
01:11:54,209 --> 01:11:55,239
The numbers are huge.

774
01:11:55,334 --> 01:11:57,621
But you can, right? She can.

775
01:11:57,751 --> 01:12:00,371
I'd have to calculate
the number of factors in each set.

776
01:12:00,544 --> 01:12:01,787
Maybe if I had a computer.

777
01:12:01,877 --> 01:12:03,619
- You don't need a computer.
- Yes I do.

778
01:12:03,711 --> 01:12:05,287
- Figure it out.
- I can't.

779
01:12:05,378 --> 01:12:08,080
I'm not dying in a fucking rat maze!

780
01:12:08,712 --> 01:12:12,125
Look. Nobody in the whole world
could do it mentally.

781
01:12:12,212 --> 01:12:15,709
Look at the numbers. 567898545.

782
01:12:15,796 --> 01:12:17,668
There's no way I can factor that!

783
01:12:17,755 --> 01:12:23,125
I can't even start on 567!
It's astronomical!

784
01:12:25,173 --> 01:12:26,085
2.

785
01:12:30,340 --> 01:12:32,296
Astronomical.

786
01:12:33,466 --> 01:12:34,663
What did you say?

787
01:12:35,216 --> 01:12:37,456
Astronomical.

788
01:12:37,967 --> 01:12:39,045
Before that.

789
01:12:40,926 --> 01:12:42,004
Factors.

790
01:12:43,176 --> 01:12:46,210
How many factors Kazan?
Of 567.

791
01:12:46,885 --> 01:12:47,798
2.

792
01:12:48,427 --> 01:12:50,169
What, are you fucking kidding?

793
01:12:50,969 --> 01:12:53,588
Kazan. How many
factors does 30 have?

794
01:12:53,719 --> 01:12:54,549
3.

795
01:12:55,220 --> 01:12:58,171
- How about 7?
- 1. Gum drop.

796
01:12:58,804 --> 01:13:00,213
I don't have any gum drops.

797
01:13:00,929 --> 01:13:01,959
Gum drop.

798
01:13:02,388 --> 01:13:07,093
Kazan. I'll give you a whole box
of gum drops for each answer.

799
01:13:07,472 --> 01:13:09,546
Gum drops come in bags.

800
01:13:09,680 --> 01:13:11,755
Okay. You want them in bags,
they are coming in bags.

801
01:13:11,848 --> 01:13:14,253
I don't like the red ones.

802
01:13:17,015 --> 01:13:20,097
- 898.
- 2.

803
01:13:21,433 --> 01:13:24,514
- 545.
- 2.

804
01:13:24,683 --> 01:13:26,176
He's giving us the factors.

805
01:13:26,767 --> 01:13:29,007
Astronomical.

806
01:13:29,892 --> 01:13:33,175
You're telling me
telethon boy is a genius?

807
01:13:34,351 --> 01:13:36,638
By those numbers,
the room should be safe.

808
01:13:37,102 --> 01:13:38,892
Only one way to find out.

809
01:13:41,019 --> 01:13:41,849
Don't!

810
01:13:46,479 --> 01:13:47,308
Safe.

811
01:13:48,479 --> 01:13:52,059
Kazan, my man.

812
01:13:55,688 --> 01:13:57,312
What's the number, buddy boy?

813
01:13:58,022 --> 01:14:01,353
Hey, right here, look here!

814
01:14:02,690 --> 01:14:04,064
Make him do it!

815
01:14:07,232 --> 01:14:09,721
Kazan, we're gonna do
some numbers now, okay?

816
01:14:09,816 --> 01:14:11,439
We like to do numbers, right?

817
01:14:11,941 --> 01:14:13,849
- Prime numbers.
- That's right.

818
01:14:14,192 --> 01:14:17,225
- Can you tell me the factor of 656?
- 2.

819
01:14:17,776 --> 01:14:20,265
- 779?
- 2.

820
01:14:20,484 --> 01:14:22,475
- 462?
- 3.

821
01:14:22,776 --> 01:14:24,056
- Clear.
- Move!

822
01:14:24,943 --> 01:14:28,025
Come on. Come on,
let's go. You too, Worth!

823
01:14:31,778 --> 01:14:35,393
Move your scawny ass, Worth.
I'm not through with you yet.

824
01:14:35,820 --> 01:14:37,064
Leaven, open that door.

825
01:14:37,237 --> 01:14:39,063
Get Einstein
working on the numbers.

826
01:14:42,530 --> 01:14:43,359
Oh, jeez.

827
01:14:43,447 --> 01:14:44,904
- Go!
- Worth!

828
01:14:45,072 --> 01:14:47,312
- Hurry!
- Leaven!

829
01:14:51,198 --> 01:14:52,146
563!

830
01:14:53,365 --> 01:14:56,280
- Please, Kazan, 563?
- You fuckers, you're dead!

831
01:14:56,824 --> 01:14:58,483
- 2.
- Clear!

832
01:15:04,450 --> 01:15:06,856
- 1.
- Trapped!

833
01:15:10,368 --> 01:15:12,110
- Check the floor.
- Is he dead?

834
01:15:13,369 --> 01:15:14,363
Not quite.

835
01:15:14,952 --> 01:15:17,358
Not even close. Worth,
I'm getting out of here and

836
01:15:17,453 --> 01:15:19,776
I'll feed you to
a fucking trap on the way.

837
01:15:28,955 --> 01:15:30,033
Where is he?

838
01:15:30,580 --> 01:15:35,321
Come here. I said
come here right nooowwww!!

839
01:15:39,998 --> 01:15:42,285
Gotchya. That way.

840
01:15:44,874 --> 01:15:46,248
- 2.
- Clear!

841
01:15:47,249 --> 01:15:48,280
- 4.
- Clear!

842
01:16:21,089 --> 01:16:23,624
Guess that proves our theory.
Numbers.

843
01:16:23,756 --> 01:16:27,086
- 4, 2, 3.
- Clear.

844
01:16:36,550 --> 01:16:38,873
Kazan!

845
01:16:58,970 --> 01:16:59,965
Listen.

846
01:17:02,221 --> 01:17:04,710
- He hasn't moved far.
- I'll go find him.

847
01:17:10,555 --> 01:17:11,586
What do you think?

848
01:17:13,014 --> 01:17:14,637
You don't have a lot of lives left.

849
01:17:32,643 --> 01:17:36,091
- Kazan!
- I didn't move.

850
01:17:36,185 --> 01:17:38,176
Yeah, good. But you're gonna have
to climb up here, okay?

851
01:17:38,269 --> 01:17:39,809
I don't like that.

852
01:17:54,813 --> 01:17:59,270
14, 26, 14.

853
01:17:59,689 --> 01:18:01,893
Worth, get back here right now!

854
01:18:01,981 --> 01:18:03,474
Five bags of gum drops.

855
01:18:03,565 --> 01:18:06,314
27 bags total.

856
01:18:06,398 --> 01:18:07,642
27 bags. Deal.

857
01:18:08,732 --> 01:18:11,933
This room's next move
takes it to the bridge!

858
01:18:12,149 --> 01:18:13,228
We're coming!

859
01:18:16,233 --> 01:18:17,063
Over here!

860
01:18:17,984 --> 01:18:21,681
Move it! We don't have
much time. Come on.

861
01:18:53,907 --> 01:18:55,697
Worth? Worth?

862
01:18:58,741 --> 01:19:00,198
This better be it.

863
01:19:01,366 --> 01:19:02,397
It should be.

864
01:19:10,701 --> 01:19:11,483
Where?

865
01:19:23,328 --> 01:19:24,276
Oh, well!

866
01:19:27,704 --> 01:19:29,612
Give me a minute. Be patient.

867
01:19:30,913 --> 01:19:33,153
- So, guess what?
- No.

868
01:19:34,664 --> 01:19:36,702
This is the room we started in.

869
01:19:37,748 --> 01:19:41,789
I was right. We should
never have moved in the first place.

870
01:20:05,627 --> 01:20:06,871
The bridge.

871
01:20:08,211 --> 01:20:08,993
Red.

872
01:20:09,711 --> 01:20:10,742
Kazan?

873
01:20:14,546 --> 01:20:18,208
- 4, 2, 4.
- Clear!

874
01:21:20,724 --> 01:21:21,553
Worth!

875
01:21:25,349 --> 01:21:26,298
Go ahead.

876
01:21:26,933 --> 01:21:28,011
What are you doing?

877
01:21:28,225 --> 01:21:29,766
You can't quit now.

878
01:21:34,101 --> 01:21:36,092
It's not your fault!

879
01:21:36,601 --> 01:21:40,975
I have nothing to live for out there.

880
01:21:44,186 --> 01:21:45,465
What is out there?

881
01:21:58,355 --> 01:22:00,974
Boundless human stupidity.

882
01:22:07,690 --> 01:22:09,017
I can live with that.

883
01:22:27,819 --> 01:22:29,395
Noooooo!!!

884
01:22:34,236 --> 01:22:36,026
Kazan! Get out through the door!

885
01:23:04,950 --> 01:23:06,229
Red, Kazan.

